1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African-American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:22,000
Today is Friday, July 8, 2011. My name is Joe Mosnier of the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

3
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:34,000
I'm with the videographer John Bishop. We are in the Jefferson Building of the Library of Congress in Washington, D.C. to do an oral history interview for the Civil Rights History Project,

4
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:42,000
which is a joint undertaking of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian's National Museum of African-American History and Culture.

5
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:50,000
And we're delighted today to be with Mr. Courtland Cox. Mr. Cox, thank you so much for sharing some of this part of the afternoon with us and thank you for coming over.

6
00:00:50,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Well, thank you for inviting me. And one other quick note, we are not recording to the camera cards but to the hard drive.

7
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:10,000
Okay. I thought I would start maybe with just having you sketch a little bit of your family history and history of the child, because I know that some of your times in Trinidad and some here.

8
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:29,000
Well, I was born in New York in Harlem in 1941. And my mother moved me and my sister to the West Indies to Trinidad where my grandmother and our family were in four years later in 1945.

9
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:48,000
I stayed in Trinidad from 1945 to 1952. And then I came back to New York after my grandmother died in 1952 and lived in Harlem for a couple of years and then moved to the Bronx.

10
00:01:48,000 --> 00:02:12,000
I attended Catholic school, St. Helena's + St. Helena's + St. Aloysius. And then, you know, went from, well, actually Catholic St. Helena's + St. Aloysius Grammar School, which was actually an interesting because it was all African-American nuns at St. Helena's + St. Aloysius' order of that.

11
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:33,000
And then, I went to St. Helena's + St. Helena's + St. Aloysius and then went to Howard University. My mother sent me to Catholic school because, you know, that at that point it cost $10 a month, which was, you know, serious money in 1952 and 54.

12
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:46,000
But also, she wanted to make sure that I had the best education that she could get. And at that point, you know, she was not too well-sold in public schools.

13
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:56,000
I grew up in the projects mostly in New York. And at that time, you could see a lot of the issues that we see today in the 50s.

14
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:15,000
I mean, you know, a lot of people were doing drugs, Moyni Marijuana and heroin. And of all the people that I grew up with, my peer group, probably only three of us graduated from high school, my system myself and one other.

15
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:27,000
And the reason I was not impacted, I think, was because of that time I spent in Trinidad, where education was stressed in my family.

16
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:38,000
So I can look back and see my cousins and their numerous women have PhDs, the men have been, you know, accomplished in education.

17
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:56,000
And it was a strong presence. I mean, there was no assumption that you would not go to college. It was assumed that you did. And, you know, and your mother, my mother said, you know, that, you know, your cousins are doing X, Y, and Z.

18
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:02,000
And we expect this of you. So, I mean, the expectation was deep and internal.

19
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:13,000
I left, when I left St. Helena's, and I was interesting, when I got to St. Helena's, there were only four African Americans in the school.

20
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:27,000
By the second year, I was by myself. So that was quite an interesting thing during that time in the Bronx, because, you know, there was a sense of isolation.

21
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:48,000
And one of the things that I felt, you know, in that time, was I would go to school, but as I was coming home, I would hide my books, because I would try to, you know, I kind of lived in both worlds, the world of going to school, and the world of being where, you know, people were.

22
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:59,000
It was very interesting, the young people I grew up with, my peer group, they, because I had an accent, because I had a different history, they had a lot of respect for me.

23
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:09,000
They respected I was different, in a sense that I would go, I was going to school, and I wasn't trying to do different things. They just, they just thought I was different, and that's fine.

24
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:13,000
And so, I had some space because of that.

25
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:17,000
Can you say a word about your sister and other siblings?

26
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:28,000
My sister is Lorraine, a Lorraine Cleveland Lorraine Cox. And, you know, she, as I said, she's the youngest sister by about two and a half years.

27
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:40,000
That's that said. And, you know, my father, I, I think the last time I saw him, I might have been ten years old. I haven't, you know, I saw him probably at that point.

28
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:55,000
So, did not see him. He was not a major factor in my life. You know, but my sister is, you know, went to during the health area and is still, you know, working in the health.

29
00:05:55,000 --> 00:06:05,000
She, she became a registered nurse, went to medical school for a while, but had some issues. And so, she's still doing them in nursing.

30
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:09,000
How did you, how did you get your attention point towards Howard?

31
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:19,000
My cousin went to Howard. My, my, my house was the stop for all my relatives coming to the United States.

32
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:34,000
My mother was the, the head of the, the family branch here. So, everybody came here. So, my cousin, Erskine, who was coming, who was a little older, but he came to go to Howard.

33
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:50,000
And he was, I guess, maybe in his late twenties, maybe early thirties. So, he came here, spent some time, you know, going to Howard, maybe two and a half years, and went to medical school, became a doctor, OB-GYN.

34
00:06:50,000 --> 00:07:02,000
And, you know, my view is, okay, well, he's doing it. My mind is well-do it. It's not, you know, and at that time, you could go and, I mean, because I had not figured out what I was going to do.

35
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:11,000
And at that time, you could go take a test, you know, I guess you didn't have to take the SATs and stuff like that. You could just go take a test.

36
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:27,000
And so, I got on the bus one day and Greyhound Bus one day, and, you know, came down to Washington by myself, took the test, went back to New York, and, you know, I passed the exam, and, you know, they said, hey, once you come on down.

37
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:52,000
And at that time, you know, tuition at Howard University was $7.50 a semester credit. So, basically, you could save a little over $100, get you $15, room was $40, board was $40, and, you could, you know, so I worked in the post office, and, you know, saved money to go to school.

38
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:56,000
Were you a political adolescent at all in your high school years?

39
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:07,000
Not political in a sense, but aware. I mean, because on the, I mean, I was part of a discussion, I mean, part of two or three discussions.

40
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:21,000
You know, I mean, you know, the question of segregation and race was much more pervasive in terms of people's assumption of what you could do, the barriers that existed, and so forth.

41
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:34,000
So, there was always discussion of that in kids who were 14 and 15. I mean, as I think back, people were very aware at 14 and 15 of what was going on in society.

42
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:50,000
Then we had another group of older guys, older, at that point, maybe in the 20s, who were in the jazz scene. So, they would talk about the culture, they talk about the music, they talk about culture, they talk about monk, they talk about all these people, you know,

43
00:08:50,000 --> 00:09:01,000
that, you know, so there was a sense of a culture and a history that was delivered by these older guys that, you know, gave me some sense of that.

44
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:14,000
But in terms of politics, no, I was aware of what was going on, but also a way of other kinds of things, but not organized kinds of political discussion, no.

45
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:26,000
Tell me what, tell me what you encountered when you got to Howard, what the campus was like, what your sense of what you were going to do was, and how you settled in.

46
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:49,000
I really, I think I didn't have a clear sense of what I was going to do. But, you know, I did have a sense of right and wrong, and kind of was impacted by what was going on, beginning to go on in the South, particularly with Emmett Till.

47
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:58,000
And I mean, I'm back to the political question, I was very much aware of what was going on in Emmett Till, I was very much aware of what was going on in Montgomery.

48
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:11,000
So, but I didn't have any, I was just aware of it, and I had a sense of it, but not, you know, any great, you know, really great depth in terms of understanding.

49
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:39,000
When I got to Howard, you know, there was, you know, places all over the place. I mean, Washington was a very segregated city at the time, whether you're talking about housing, whether you were talking about black and white ads in the Washington Post, whether you were talking about the police department, whether you were talking about trying, trying clothes on in the, in the various department stores, I mean, all those things existed.

50
00:10:39,000 --> 00:11:08,000
So, you know, I was faced with it in a way that I wasn't faced with it in New York. Also, at that point, with the city, and so there was a small group of people who decided to do stuff at Glen Echo Park Park in Washington, and we formed the NAG, you know, and some of the people who, you know, later went on to really be prominent and snickwool or part of that.

51
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:25,000
And, you know, we did two things. We did sympathetic actions for things going on and south, but we did, you know, we went out to the Eastern Shore of Maryland and demonstrated there.

52
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:42,000
We, and Stokely Carmichael, Carmichael, who was in school with me at the time, was famous for helping to organize these demonstrations because he would promise, okay, we're going to go demonstrate, but we got a great party after the demonstrations.

53
00:11:42,000 --> 00:12:00,000
And, you know, and so, you know, you know, young people want to do that. Some of the other things that we did, while I was at Howard, I mean, RFK Stadium, when the Redskins were first here, we picketed it because there were no African American football players.

54
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:27,000
We, we, Route 40, which was segregated, the route from Washington, New York, we were, you know, and involved in those demonstrations. We worked with Julius W. Hobson, who was at Corps, senior to, to, we were his shock troops. I mean, Julius was, you know, older than we were, but when he wanted a demonstration, he recalled on us to, to, to be, you know, the shock troops.

55
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:45,000
And we did other things at Howard. We, when we had the outside things that we did in terms of demonstrations, but we also created Project Awareness. And Project Awareness, I mean, the first three things that we did. I mean, I'll never forget them.

56
00:12:45,000 --> 00:13:00,000
First, the first was a debate between Bayard Rustin Rustin, Rustin and Malcolm X on the question of segregation versus integration. The second was a debate on, with Norman Thomas and Norman Thomas on the question of thermonuclear warfare.

57
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:19,000
On the third was a symposium with James Baldwin, Ossie Davis, John Oliver Killens moderated by Sterling A. Brown. And, and for the after party, Sidney Poitier flew in so that, you know, just to see what the boys were doing.

58
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:38,000
So, I mean, we, you know, for people our age at that time, we were, I mean, we were whatever we were. I mean, and then the other thing that was also clear, you know, we were also in the student council, you know, Tom Kahn who was a member of NAG was the treasure of the student council.

59
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:53,000
Stokely Carmichael was in the student council, you know, a student government. And then the other thing that was Mike Thillwell, who was, you know, a member of NAG, ran the newspaper and got great awards for the quality of the newspaper.

60
00:13:53,000 --> 00:14:08,000
So, we functioned at, you know, internally externally in terms of demonstrations, but in terms of how it, in terms of people who could organize and do things, we were there. We were in the leadership of it.

61
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:19,000
And we were also encouraged by a lot of the professors because they thought they adopted us as their children, particularly Sterling A. Brown.

62
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:40,000
He would invite us to his house. He would, you know, have, you know, discussions. He would talk to us about the boys. He would talk to us about, you know, other people that we've heard about. He would, you know, he would talk to, he would, you know, not only play at his house, the jazz music or the blues.

63
00:14:40,000 --> 00:15:03,000
He would come to our dormitory and talk about the history. He would talk about the poetry. You know, we had, you know, others, Conrad Snowden. We, you know, we had other professors. You know, we had others who, you know, just sort that we were doing what they would like to do.

64
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:08,000
And they tried to give us all the encouragement that they could.

65
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:16,000
Tell me a little bit more about this, this group and your role in relation to all these, all these other folks who mentioned.

66
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:23,000
Well, the nag was really run by three people, three large egos, I think.

67
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:31,000
Ed Brown, who is, you know, rap's older brother, Stokely Carmichael of myself.

68
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:46,000
And I think, you know, people look to us in terms of, of the, you know, in terms of leadership issues. I mean, I think that,

69
00:15:46,000 --> 00:16:02,000
and when it, when a lot of, I did a lot of stuff on the project, awareness stuff in terms of organization and pulling it together. Also a lot of stuff on the, the demonstrations and so forth.

70
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:11,000
I didn't do too much in a student council. Didn't do too much on the student newspapers. But in those two, we were very active.

71
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:19,000
Tell me about how you, how nagged and, and all of so many of you deepened your engagement with SNCC.

72
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:27,000
Well, I mean, at that point, SNCC was, SNCC in the early days was a student, a student non-von coordinating committee.

73
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:34,000
So it was really a coordination of student groups across the country.

74
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:42,000
So therefore, nag was one of the student groups across the country. You know, Nashville was another, Atlanta was another.

75
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:51,000
So we were just part of, so we sat in with, you know, they were, I sat on the, the coordinating council for SNCC.

76
00:16:51,000 --> 00:17:00,000
And I guess on the executive council, it's a committee at some point, you know, to, you know, help pull the organization together.

77
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:09,000
Can you travel to Atlanta? Yes. Yeah, I used to be going down on highway 29. And I remember gas was 29 cents a gallon.

78
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:17,000
Now I couldn't drive, but I'd ride down there. So gas was 29 cents a gallon, cigarettes were 20 cents a pack.

79
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:28,000
Did you smoke? I used to smoke. I used to smoke until 1971. And I was on my way to Africa. And I saw, I was at La Guardia Airport.

80
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:37,000
And I saw that cigarettes had gotten to 70 cents a pack. And I said, I'm in a machine. I said, I know where this is going.

81
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:42,000
It's time for me to end this conversation. So I stopped smoking.

82
00:17:42,000 --> 00:17:52,000
Are there interesting, interesting things that stand out vividly in your memory from those early trips to Atlanta for those SNCC meetings?

83
00:17:52,000 --> 00:17:59,000
The SNCC meetings or the trips, which were, I mean, I'm well, they both are very interesting, but I think you have the SNCC.

84
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:08,000
They were, I mean, we, they're good thing about the interesting, the meetings were, and the discussions were interminable.

85
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:21,000
And we talked about everything. May I think probably the thing that's most important, as I think about, I just kind of think of, I've just thought about this lately.

86
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:35,000
You know, most of the young people were asking why, and they, they given the basis, the given the kinds of things that they face.

87
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:45,000
They were asking why. At the SNCC meetings, we thought about how to change, and everybody said, why not, okay?

88
00:18:45,000 --> 00:19:13,000
I mean, paraphrasing that famous poem. It seems to me the difference, and the real genius of the young people, and we're talking 17 to 22, you know, of that group, was that we move from asking why the situation existed, the way it did, to talking about why not change it in a way that we should be living.

89
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:25,000
And once you cross that barrier, and don't feel you have to ask those who created the situation to, to make the change for you, then you were free.

90
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:40,000
And I therefore, I think the things that struck me about those conversations, about the 17 to 22 years, that the barriers of, of normal thinking and intellectual thought were broken.

91
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:53,000
And the discussions about where we should be going, what we should be doing, and so forth were limitless. And I think that's the thing that, you know, I didn't strike me then, but it strikes me now.

92
00:19:53,000 --> 00:20:03,000
And also looking back in that context, you mentioned that your peer group in the Bronx, saw you as, could accept you as someone who was somehow a little bit different, because you like experiencing it.

93
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:04,000
Right.

94
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:23,000
So, was there any parallel then to your experience inside this group of young activists at SNCC, or did you feel that your personal history distinguished you in some way that mattered, say to your participation in those conversations, your perspectives, your philosophy?

95
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:52,000
I didn't think so, okay, but I mean, there was always this West Indian discussion, you know, it even appeared in Time or Newsweek magazine, where people considered people like Stokely, Ivanhoe Donaldson and myself, you know, to be, quote, have a different view, because we came from environments that might have been a little less restrictive.

96
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:55,000
I didn't, I never bought into that.

97
00:20:55,000 --> 00:21:02,000
Tell me if you were about, actually I want to take it back to, have you tell me about the Rustin, not Mextebae?

98
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:13,000
Oh, it was amazing. It was amazing. They had just built Cramton Auditorium at Howard University. The capacity was 1500.

99
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:29,000
And, I mean, the leading up to it, we tried to get the professor who was the head of the government to moderate the debate. I'm not going to say his name.

100
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:35,000
He thought it was beneath him to have Malcolm X at Howard University.

101
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:53,000
We had, we went to Emmett Dorsey, who was a professor at Howard, a wonderful, a big bear of a man, who would say in his class that racism is architect tonic to the Constitution of the United States, and he would point to the three fifths clause.

102
00:21:53,000 --> 00:22:00,000
He, you know, he agreed to moderate the debate.

103
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:10,000
We had a dinner before the debate with Malcolm in Bayard Rustin Rustin, and Professor Dorsey was talking.

104
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:20,000
And Malcolm said, Professor, I think we better let you speak tonight, because you have much more information than anybody in this room, which was really true.

105
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:30,000
We got to the debate. I mean, Malcolm had, maybe about 300 as followers in the front.

106
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:36,000
Baya gets up, and I think he speaks first. He does speak first.

107
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:50,000
Every participant had 30 minutes to speak. Baya speaks 15 minutes, and he says, you always hear my point of view through the Drum and Spear Bookstore + Drum and Spear Press everything.

108
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:58,000
I now want to give Malcolm 15 of my minutes to help to give him to present.

109
00:22:58,000 --> 00:23:13,000
And Malcolm was, I mean, a dynamite speaker. And the thing that struck me was Malcolm, if you listen the message of the grass to the grass roots, that's basically the speech that he gave, or the album and this thing.

110
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:18,000
But, and I hadn't heard it. This is 1961. I hadn't heard it.

111
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:28,000
And he would tell a joke or something like that, or clap, and they'd be applauding. And when he did that, his people would then do that.

112
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:43,000
I mean, the discipline was phenomenal. I said, whoa, what is this? And I will tell you, from that debate, people at Howard saw us different.

113
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:52,000
And that we could bring Malcolm X and Bayard Rustin Rustin Rustin, people were pounding on the door the whole night trying to get in.

114
00:23:52,000 --> 00:24:02,000
I mean, because that was considered a big auditorium, we brought, I mean, you know, kind of presaz, and all sorts of things there.

115
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:15,000
People looked at us totally different after that. I mean, students, hey, these guys have something that we don't have. I mean, I think that's kind of, that gave us a little cachet that we probably wouldn't have had on narrowly.

116
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:19,000
Yeah. What was your early sense of, of the words?

117
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:36,000
Okay. We took a short break. I was going to ask about, you've just mentioned the Malcolm and Bayard Rustin Rustin Rustin debate, and these other things and how this cachet attached.

118
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:42,000
I'm remembering now that the question I want to ask was shifting themes a little bit.

119
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:58,000
Early on, what was your, how did you gauge the prospects of substantial, true kind of structural change through the nonviolent protest strategies that were emerging through SNCC?

120
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:11,000
We had big debates about that. We had, we had, and the national group had one view that Howard Group had another.

121
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:31,000
The national group believed in nonviolences of philosophy in a way of life. I mean, and John, I mean, John is probably the, you know, the post-a-child for that, you know, Diane Nash + James Lawson, those guys.

122
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:48,000
Well, at Howard, we viewed nonviolences as a tactic, you know, and, you know, one of the things that the nonviolent people of philosophy, those people, they felt that, you know, you could appeal to men's hearts.

123
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:59,000
You know, my view in which I've said to them was that you might as well appeal to their livers because they're both organs of the body. There was nothing to that.

124
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:11,000
You did not, you engaged in nonviolence because the other side had overwhelming force. There was not a sense that the other side would do the right thing if you told them.

125
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:22,000
Because at the end of the day, the other side knew what it was doing to you better than you did. So it's not that they didn't know what they were doing. They wanted to do it.

126
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:38,000
So, I mean, that, so we had huge, huge, I mean, that was the source of early tension. I mean, early 61, 62, so forth. We did not believe in nonviolences philosophy.

127
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:53,000
I have a parallel question in these early years, especially when things heat up in the South, 62, 63. What was your evolving sense of what you might be able to expect from the federal government?

128
00:26:53,000 --> 00:26:56,000
You have much of anything.

129
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:11,000
I mean, I think there were individuals particularly John Doar, particularly Burke Marshall at the Civil Rights Division, who were, you know, very helpful.

130
00:27:11,000 --> 00:27:25,000
But I mean, I, you know, there was a story sort of like in the house was bombed in Macomb. I think this was 63, 64, maybe 64.

131
00:27:25,000 --> 00:27:30,000
And we went down there. You were in Mississippi.

132
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:48,000
We went Mississippi, I'm sorry. We went to McComb. The FBI was there. They said to us, look, don't make any mistake about it. We're here to protect the evidence. We're not here to guard you or protect you.

133
00:27:48,000 --> 00:28:02,000
Okay, that's first. Then the guy said to us, look, how many guns do you have? And we said we don't have any guns. He said, well, I've got two and I'm scared to death.

134
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:16,000
So you got, yeah, two issues. First, their mandate was limited because, you know, of both the political, local political issues, and which affected the federal political issues.

135
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:31,000
And at the end of the day, most of these guys as individuals thought they would be overwhelmed. So I mean, you know, we, you know, we tried to communicate to the federal government as much as we could communicate.

136
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:46,000
And tried to, in certain circumstances, try to do that. But, you know, many of the people in SNCC, including myself, felt that, you know, most of those agents who came from the South were of the South.

137
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:52,000
And therefore sympathetic, not to us, but, you know, the communities that they lived in.

138
00:28:52,000 --> 00:29:00,000
Sure. Let me bring you back to 62 from in the, in the spring, you and Stokely Carmichael, and I think one or two others sat in by Robert Kennedy's office.

139
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:10,000
Oh, yes, we did. Tom Kahn was the other third person. Tom Kahn and Tom Kahn. You, you've really done your research. Can you recall that?

140
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:25,000
Yes. It was, it was funny. We went there and we went to the, to Kennedy's office. And I think they went to a quandary as to what to do.

141
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:38,000
And so basically they just said, okay, just leave them there and stuff. And then, later the afternoon, they were going to come and move us out of the building.

142
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:57,000
And then they would take us out. So, which Khan, who started calling the Drum and Spear Bookstore + Drum and Spear Press from, from Kennedy's office, and included the Soviet Drum and Spear Bookstore + Drum and Spear Press and the people that he called.

143
00:29:57,000 --> 00:30:07,000
So then they came at the end of the day, and they were, you know, we went limp and they were dragging us out.

144
00:30:07,000 --> 00:30:19,000
So as they were dragging us out, they probably got maybe 50, 60 feet down the hall. Stokely says, wait a minute, wait a minute. I forgot something in the office.

145
00:30:19,000 --> 00:30:34,000
So he gets up, goes and gets the stuff in the office, goes back to exactly where he was. So, okay. So, so I mean, so they, they just took us out the office and just say, buy, see you.

146
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:41,000
You know, so I mean, you know, that's what I remember about it.

147
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:50,000
It's interesting how one of the, one of the things that's so interesting about doing these interviews in 2011 here is that emotional mood about all this shift. It's so much.

148
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:51,000
Right.

149
00:30:51,000 --> 00:30:57,000
And we say it and we recall these things with a smile. And yet, you were there for what we're just deadly serious reason?

150
00:30:57,000 --> 00:31:00,000
Oh, yeah. No, no, we were very serious. Absolutely.

151
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:15,000
And not because we thought that the Kennedy administration, first of all, we thought that the Kennedy administration, particularly the way they dealt with Martin King, you know, earlier, was, you know, basically an opportunist approach to things.

152
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:37,000
We thought that, you know, Bobby Kennedy and the Justice Department was not being very serious. They were also very opportunistic and had a view that they would only do what they were pushed to do, even though the law of the land, you know, which changed in 54 to be, you know, be on the side of the ending of segregation.

153
00:31:37,000 --> 00:31:47,000
You know, they, they, they are brought into the go slow approach and don't disturb approach and look, don't cause any political trouble for my brother approach.

154
00:31:47,000 --> 00:31:57,000
You know, so we felt that at the end of the day, they were about themselves and not about, you know, making this country a better place for everyone.

155
00:31:57,000 --> 00:32:10,000
Yeah. Yeah. Let me ask about two things that obviously you've given, you've been asked to give many interviews over the years and two episodes are often the focus of a lot of attention.

156
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:15,000
And I want to sort of take them up together because in some ways they have a relation. You can tell them if you agree.

157
00:32:15,000 --> 00:32:44,000
The struggle over the jungle speech of Washington in August of 63 and a year later, the Atlantic City MFBP struggle in the, the, the, the, the, don't have any connection because in both those instances, I think I think of them as having to do with that, that forceful and quite idealistic and quite hopeful push.

158
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:50,000
Really bumping into up against some very, very rugged power.

159
00:32:50,000 --> 00:32:59,000
No, I think I would take them too separately because I think the Atlantic City had a much more profound impact than, than much of Washington.

160
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:04,000
Okay. The March on Washington, I was the representative for snake.

161
00:33:05,000 --> 00:33:28,000
And the steering committee, the steering committee. And for whatever reasons, at this point, I can't remember, I passed our John speech before the March to the Drum and Spear Bookstore + Drum and Spear Press, because I assume I was trying to promote John speech. I mean, that's why you do that.

162
00:33:28,000 --> 00:33:43,000
And then we are at the March and John, we get a call, Archbishop of Boyle says that he is not going to participate in the March on Washington.

163
00:33:43,000 --> 00:34:04,000
You know, if the criticism of Kennedy's administration and the whole reference to March and through the South, the, sure, but I think that last part about March and through the Shows is Sherman is, is a little, you know, was a ruse because the real, they did not want the Kennedy administration criticized.

164
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:26,000
And, you know, we at that point, when I say we, John Lewis, Jim Forman, myself, you know, told Archbishop, by it came to us at that point, and we told, you know, you could tell Archbishop of Boyle to go straight to hell.

165
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:38,000
And he changed us to the speech. We were not going to change. And then what Boyle did, and Boyle is a very clever person, he went and got a Philip Randolph.

166
00:34:38,000 --> 00:34:51,000
A. Philip Randolph said, I know, you know, you know, he gave us our propers, but he said, look, I have worked since 1941 to make this happen.

167
00:34:51,000 --> 00:35:05,000
And it is important that the coalition is held together. And it is out of respect for A. Philip Randolph that we were, you know, we went in the back of the Lincoln Memorial,

168
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:27,000
Jim Forman, John Lewis, Miljard Forman, myself, and we changed John's speech. Now, the way that was perceived and snick at that point was that particularly me and Forman, we caved in.

169
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:42,000
And so the criticism was individual to us from the snick people. It wasn't the broader society. I think Atlantic City was a lot different.

170
00:35:42,000 --> 00:36:01,000
I mean, people worked, I mean, people worked all summer. They faced tremendous, you know, hostilities. And they thought that the rules, they played by the rules that they were supposed to be playing.

171
00:36:01,000 --> 00:36:22,000
And everybody was engaged in that. We went to, we went to Atlantic City with the sense that if, again, if you presented the facts to the nation, then it would make a difference.

172
00:36:22,000 --> 00:36:38,000
The first thing, the first clue was when Fannie Lou Hamer was speaking, Lyndon Johnson called a non-serious Drum and Spear Bookstore + Drum and Spear Press conference to say that today is Tuesday. Okay. And to take her off the ear.

173
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:58,000
But in the bowels of Atlantic City Convention Center, Bob Moses, Charlie Cobb, Ivanhoe Donaldson, all of us were, I mean, people were scrubbed, we put on suits and ties. We, I mean, you know, all that sort of stuff, some of us hadn't had ties on for some time.

174
00:36:58,000 --> 00:37:12,000
But we went around and we were able to pigeonhole enough people like Rep. Edith Green and others to support, you know, the Mississippi Freedom Bank, at least at the Credentials Committee level.

175
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:35,000
Then the, when it was known that we had enough to, to enough representatives, the Lyndon Baines Johnson really started acting ugly. He called, he called, he would hungry and he told them, if you want the vice presidency, you better stop these people.

176
00:37:35,000 --> 00:38:00,000
He called people who were up for judge ships. He said, if you don't do this, you are through booking. Now, we had the list of people and a congressman, whose name I will not put out here at this point, you know, came to us and I remember, Bob Moses and I were in the meeting.

177
00:38:01,000 --> 00:38:25,000
And the congressman asked us for the list of people who weren't supported. Because he said, what he wanted to do was show, you know, Lyndon Baines that he had, in fact, the kind of, you know, support and therefore, you know, therefore to be able to move the agenda in our direction.

178
00:38:25,000 --> 00:38:40,000
Bob Moses just looked at him and stared. And I said to Bob, do you think he's going to steal the list? Bob hesitated a little more and then he gave him the list.

179
00:38:41,000 --> 00:38:56,000
You know, if you've seen, if I saw the list, you've seen it. What that congressman did was use that to get the Johnson administration to go after each one of these people to get them to capitulate.

180
00:38:56,000 --> 00:39:09,000
These are the, these are the minority, but sufficient minority to do a minority report. Yes. So, so this congressman, you know, took the list and went and then, you know,

181
00:39:09,000 --> 00:39:18,000
gave us, you know, you know, I wouldn't use the word betrayed, but it was close.

182
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:33,000
At that point, you know, we had, you know, worked the whole time. We had, you know, basically played by the rules that was established.

183
00:39:34,000 --> 00:39:50,000
And when it came out that, you know, they had collapsed the minority, a group of minority representatives who would participate in minority report.

184
00:39:51,000 --> 00:40:05,000
What happened was they then offered two seats, you know, in the balcony somewhere, two seats on the floor and then the others could be sitting in the balcony.

185
00:40:06,000 --> 00:40:33,000
And people like, you know, people that we quote on our side, I would say National Counselor Churches, you know, AFL, CIO, Martin King, you know, NAACP, the Joseph L. Rauh Jr, you know, everybody, everybody.

186
00:40:34,000 --> 00:40:38,000
You said, this, you should accept this.

187
00:40:40,000 --> 00:40:49,000
We said, okay, well, just, I mean, I'd always kind of worked with the people and was Bob's idea. All right.

188
00:40:49,000 --> 00:40:57,000
We met in the church, he said, Bob's for you is, okay, if you want them to accept it, make your presentation.

189
00:40:58,000 --> 00:41:06,000
And they presented and they, you know, talked about it and the people said, we didn't come up here for this pretense.

190
00:41:06,000 --> 00:41:15,000
You know, we came here believing that if you played by the rules, in fact, the rules would be observed.

191
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:38,000
So that, you know, so that not, it wasn't only the Johnson administration, it wasn't only, you know, Hubert Humphrey, it was the whole liberal establishment that said, no, the rule, when it comes to power, these rules don't obtain.

192
00:41:38,000 --> 00:41:52,000
So at the end of the day, the refusal of, you know, the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party to deal with that, you know, so-called compromise.

193
00:41:53,000 --> 00:42:11,000
You know, and the kind of sense that power prevails, not the sense of, you know, the ideals and the things that we, you know, people espoused, you know, you know, capitalism always trumps democracy.

194
00:42:11,000 --> 00:42:23,000
That, you know, then people were able to see it firsthand. I mean, I mean, we, you know, 64, you know, I was 23, you know, everybody else was around that.

195
00:42:23,000 --> 00:42:32,000
And they said, hey, this is the way it happens, huh? You know, not all that stuff we read in the books, this is the stuff that I wasn't idealism.

196
00:42:32,000 --> 00:42:39,000
These were the rules that you put out there. This wasn't stuff we thought up. This was what you said the party rules were.

197
00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:48,000
And when it came to the, the deal came down, this is the way it came down. And then people said, hey, we no longer trust you.

198
00:42:48,000 --> 00:42:57,000
I mean, I think people then started disengaging from the electoral process and the, and what people considered foolishness.

199
00:42:57,000 --> 00:43:09,000
So, if you want to just have a little bit, um, step back to when we started to go to the convention, just line out what you anticipate and what the content is.

200
00:43:09,000 --> 00:43:19,000
Right. I think when we started with the, you know, we, first of all, we had worked, we created the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party.

201
00:43:19,000 --> 00:43:39,000
We went to all the counties in Mississippi. We held meeting after meeting, you know, when the, you know, the rules of the party said that in fact, if you did these things, you would be seated because you would be representing these things and you, you function by the rules.

202
00:43:39,000 --> 00:43:49,000
So, that when we went to Atlantic City, having functioned by the rules of the, of the Democratic Party itself, we expected to be seated.

203
00:43:49,000 --> 00:44:04,000
We expected to be, you know, the Democratic Party in Mississippi. And in fact, when we got to, you know, we got to Atlantic City, we found out the rules had changed.

204
00:44:04,000 --> 00:44:23,000
Let me, let me have you, um, if you would please, um, talk about the transition then after August 64 to Alabama. And the way you thought about widening the project with new approaches to what I think the term you had used was the unqualified.

205
00:44:23,000 --> 00:44:38,000
Yeah. I think of all the things I have done, I didn't snake. I'm most proud and most, I like what we did in Lowns best.

206
00:44:38,000 --> 00:44:59,000
Um, the, the reason we went to Lowns County was to deal with the kind of violence, particularly shooting of Violet, Lou, so when we went there, you found a county that was 80% African American and they were four registered voters.

207
00:44:59,000 --> 00:45:24,000
Now, the, the stradded, the Alabama had a law that allowed you to have a political party at the county level. It also had a, a rooster would said for the right above it.

208
00:45:24,000 --> 00:45:44,000
Now, the question that became how do you achieve political power and how do you achieve regime change? Because before we were all talking about, um, you know,

209
00:45:44,000 --> 00:45:59,000
registering people to vote, we were all talking about, you know, if you presented the facts, if you did that and you ever, you played by the rules then, you know, the rules would be supported.

210
00:45:59,000 --> 00:46:11,000
And 65, the view was, okay, here are the rules and how do we manipulate them to achieve our own because we're not taking them to anybody because we know what that's going to be.

211
00:46:11,000 --> 00:46:21,000
So that we're saying, okay, you have a 80% majority, then you want to be able to run the county.

212
00:46:21,000 --> 00:46:32,000
So the, you know, officer sheriff, officer of county assessor, when a tax assessor, county clerk, county court, you know, I mean the judge.

213
00:46:32,000 --> 00:46:48,000
And the problem was a lot of people run were they did not read a right and two, they, the idea, they didn't know a lot about the offices or responsibility offices.

214
00:46:48,000 --> 00:47:00,000
And three, you had to get them to believe they could do it. So what we did, Jack Minnis, who was the research guy in Atlanta, was absolutely brilliant.

215
00:47:00,000 --> 00:47:15,000
I mean, just absolutely brilliant. We researched the laws. And once we found that you could have a party on the county level, we could say, all right, what does it take to build a party at the county?

216
00:47:15,000 --> 00:47:30,000
So we then researched the roles and responsibilities of each of the offices. Now we knew that people were not going to sit down and read law books.

217
00:47:30,000 --> 00:47:40,000
So what we did was we created comic books, which talked about the roles and responsibilities.

218
00:47:40,000 --> 00:47:56,000
We got people who would agree to run for sheriff and we gave them the comic books and we passed the comic books and we put their pictures out there so that people could see them in that particular context.

219
00:47:56,000 --> 00:48:07,000
The other thing that we did, you know, was we created a propaganda piece called Mr. Black Man.

220
00:48:07,000 --> 00:48:17,000
And it's a story I developed with Jennifer Lawson, who is now working with PBS. She did the graphics I did the text.

221
00:48:17,000 --> 00:48:30,000
And I used a phrase that I heard from a woman in Mississippi. She said, you know, us Black people have been using our mouths to do two things.

222
00:48:30,000 --> 00:48:44,000
To eat and say, yes, it's now time we say no. So I used that to create a sense that we have been, you know, doing all these kinds of things.

223
00:48:44,000 --> 00:48:56,000
And we've been eating and saying, yes, it's now time we support Mr. Black Man and it could be for, you know, so and so for sheriff, so and so for taxes, that's a so and so.

224
00:48:56,000 --> 00:49:04,000
Because our argument was it's no use protesting police brutality by the sheriff.

225
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:11,000
The way to deal with it is get a new sheriff who exceeds to your view of the world.

226
00:49:11,000 --> 00:49:24,000
So then we, you know, got people to believe. Now as you know, we went on the plantations and, you know, and obviously there, you know, there was a lot of reaction.

227
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:32,000
They two people out of their houses, you know, violence and so forth. But what we found in Lowns County, Mr., his name is Mr. Jackson.

228
00:49:32,000 --> 00:49:42,000
We found, I mean, he's a guy who owned his land. I mean, he was a guy who was the salt of the earth. When you see him, it looked like he was just he's coming out of the earth.

229
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:51,000
He was just very strong and, you know, and his view was he was quiet. He wasn't highly educated or that, but he was very strong.

230
00:49:51,000 --> 00:49:59,000
And he gave us his house and he would stay up on night to protect us with his gun.

231
00:49:59,000 --> 00:50:10,000
So that, you know, so that basically our thinking in 65, it said no, no more about going and taking these rules. No, you got to create your own rules.

232
00:50:10,000 --> 00:50:19,000
You got to now assume power. You got to now the discussion is no longer about protests. The discussion is about power.

233
00:50:19,000 --> 00:50:33,000
How do you now assume power, you know, given you have a demographic, you know, advantage and how do you move that discussion? You do your research, you do, you, you now understand how to go about it.

234
00:50:33,000 --> 00:50:48,000
And basically over time, you know, convincing people like John Hulett and others to run for sheriff and others that we were able to now be able to take over every position in the county.

235
00:50:48,000 --> 00:51:01,000
You know, and I wrote a pamphlet and I can't find it anymore. You know, I gave away a lot of the stuff that I used to have, but it was a pamphlet that I wrote called what would paraphrasing a biblical thing?

236
00:51:01,000 --> 00:51:14,000
What would it profit a man to gain the vote and not be able to control it? Because at that point, the discussion of control and organization to move that control was particularly important.

237
00:51:14,000 --> 00:51:29,000
Let me ask a couple of things. Let me have you describe, you alluded to the atmosphere of violence in Lansk County and in that, in that era.

238
00:51:29,000 --> 00:51:38,000
Can you say a little more because I know that for example, Jonathan Daniels is a king of the county seat outside the, when they're sprung from jail that's been wanting.

239
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:46,000
Just a little bit about the experience of being there and confronting that and observing that as a.

240
00:51:46,000 --> 00:51:59,000
Well, I was not exactly, I mean, the reason we went into Lansk was to show after Jonathan was killed and Ruby Sales was almost killed, you know, that we were not going to be afraid.

241
00:51:59,000 --> 00:52:18,000
So we came in after that and, you know, particularly people like Stokely Carmichael, Ralph Fethiston, Willie Ricks, you know, Bob Mants, you know, we came in after that to make sure that we were going to show that we were not going to be run out.

242
00:52:18,000 --> 00:52:31,000
And so, I mean, I think for the community, which was, you know, was there, you know, saying that we ourselves would live in the community.

243
00:52:31,000 --> 00:52:40,000
We would be at risk with you was the same thing. I mean, and I mean, this house we lived in is interesting.

244
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:47,000
You know, I had no running water. So we had to prime the pump in the morning to get our water.

245
00:52:47,000 --> 00:53:02,000
It had a one-butane gas heater in the living room and it had a hole in the roof. So when it rained, you have to have a pen in your bed so it wouldn't rain on the bed.

246
00:53:02,000 --> 00:53:13,000
But I mean, you know, so, and when so when you wanted to get relief, excuse me for a second.

247
00:53:13,000 --> 00:53:30,000
So we, you know, we used to go to Selma to get a bath or take a shower to go to a chicken chat, listen to some music and get some fried chicken, and drive back to the county.

248
00:53:30,000 --> 00:53:40,000
But I mean, people saw us living there, you know, day to day and gave him comfort that, you know, we were serious people.

249
00:53:40,000 --> 00:53:55,000
And that, you know, the kind of violence that was visited upon the county by, you know, the people who killed Daniels and almost shot Ruby Sales and so forth, that we would, you know, would stand up to it.

250
00:53:55,000 --> 00:54:07,000
So, I think, you know, for our living in the county or living where we, or Southwest Georgia or Mississippi, you know, that county, I mean, that was Snicks trademark.

251
00:54:07,000 --> 00:54:12,000
We lived where we worked, I mean, as opposed to, you know, dropping in and dropping out.

252
00:54:12,000 --> 00:54:21,000
You personally, how did you, how did you deal with that kind of pressure here?

253
00:54:21,000 --> 00:54:30,000
I think I always told myself, there is fear there, and you shouldn't be paralyzed by it.

254
00:54:30,000 --> 00:54:39,000
I mean, I remember once, we were driving, I was driving with this young guy, John Jackson, Mr. Jackson's younger son.

255
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:44,000
And these guys started chasing us with a pickup truck and they had guns.

256
00:54:44,000 --> 00:54:54,000
I mean, and we were going, I mean, we must have, on those dirt roads, we were probably going 70, 80 miles an hour.

257
00:54:54,000 --> 00:55:04,000
And, you know, you tell yourself that you could deal with it. I mean, you fantasize all sorts of stuff.

258
00:55:04,000 --> 00:55:12,000
Like, for example, I always thought that, okay, I could probably get away with somebody who had a gun.

259
00:55:12,000 --> 00:55:17,000
But I had a problem with an Alabama because I thought they would use bombs.

260
00:55:17,000 --> 00:55:28,000
So, I was never, I was more nervous about Alabama than I was Mississippi because I thought they would bomb and Mrs. Alabama and shoot in Mississippi.

261
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:36,000
And therefore, you keep telling yourself, okay, don't be paralyzed. This is a dangerous situation. Don't be paralyzed.

262
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:47,000
Now, sometimes I remember I looked around in the trial of Collie Leroy Wilkins Jr, who had shot Viola Liuzzo.

263
00:55:47,000 --> 00:55:52,000
I looked around in the courtroom and I was the only person of color in the whole courtroom.

264
00:55:52,000 --> 00:55:59,000
And I started thinking, all right, what were the people, what were the kids that I went to college doing?

265
00:55:59,000 --> 00:56:07,000
I mean, they were doing that. And I said to you know, you're really crazy. I mean, this is a little dangerous here.

266
00:56:07,000 --> 00:56:25,000
I mean, so I mean, I think when you, I think for, when you are in it, you have mechanisms that go into place that don't calculate the danger or deflect the danger from you.

267
00:56:26,000 --> 00:56:32,000
I think it's only if something actually happens to somebody you know it brings it home.

268
00:56:32,000 --> 00:56:39,000
I think when you get outside of it, you think about, you know, that was a little, little interesting.

269
00:56:39,000 --> 00:56:47,000
So, I mean, I think that, you know, I was affected. I mean, I always try to rationalize it.

270
00:56:47,000 --> 00:56:57,000
You know, there were others in SNCC who were not so lucky. But I went through a series of rationalizations. I mean, that's the way I dealt with it.

271
00:56:57,000 --> 00:57:03,000
Let me ask you about the 65, 66 period in SNCC.

272
00:57:03,000 --> 00:57:04,000
Okay.

273
00:57:04,000 --> 00:57:06,000
And Carmack will replace his Lewis.

274
00:57:06,000 --> 00:57:07,000
Yes.

275
00:57:07,000 --> 00:57:19,000
White circles. Just here. How do you move through that period? You can describe it and your perspective on those, those transition?

276
00:57:19,000 --> 00:57:35,000
I think, I think basically which goes back to Atlantic City, the organization was becoming much more militant in a sense that the whole sense of,

277
