01:39:47,480 --> 01:39:51,480
We're not able to focus on the economic discussion,

700
01:39:51,480 --> 01:39:57,480
because what we have is, you know, an information economy.

701
01:39:57,480 --> 01:40:01,480
And things, you know, manufacturing and so forth,

702
01:40:01,480 --> 01:40:04,480
while important, they are not the drivers.

703
01:40:04,480 --> 01:40:13,480
I mean, intellectual property and the ability to conceive ideas and move the discussion is particularly important.

704
01:40:13,480 --> 01:40:22,480
And that the kind of literacy that's necessary that, you know, in order going forward,

705
01:40:22,480 --> 01:40:29,480
it, you know, includes both English, but includes math and computers.

706
01:40:29,480 --> 01:40:37,480
So therefore, we now have to think and conceive of these things, you know, a lot differently.

707
01:40:37,480 --> 01:40:45,480
And I think my role and role of people like myself is to understand what the fundamentals are.

708
01:40:45,480 --> 01:40:49,480
Now, one of the things that I was talking about most is the other day.

709
01:40:49,480 --> 01:40:56,480
And, you know, he was saying that nothing we did was really radical.

710
01:40:56,480 --> 01:41:03,480
You know, getting people to vote, you know, sitting at a lunch counter and organizing politically is not radical.

711
01:41:03,480 --> 01:41:08,480
What was radical is who we tried to include in the discussion.

712
01:41:08,480 --> 01:41:15,480
You know, so that, to me, is the same fight that we have to understand, we have to bring.

713
01:41:15,480 --> 01:41:18,480
But we have to broaden the economic base.

714
01:41:18,480 --> 01:41:30,480
We have to include, you know, particularly not only African-Americans, but poor whites, you know, who are being used as soldiers for, you know, for purposes that nobody,

715
01:41:30,480 --> 01:41:32,480
they don't even care about them.

716
01:41:32,480 --> 01:41:40,480
They talk all of heroes. And then when they come back here, you know, nobody cares about them, you know, you know, Native Americans and so forth.

717
01:41:40,480 --> 01:41:49,480
So we now have to say all of these people at the bottom now have to be part of the American economy.

718
01:41:49,480 --> 01:41:57,480
And they have to begin to get a quality education that allows them to participate in the American economy.

719
01:41:57,480 --> 01:42:05,480
And those people who have intellectual property should be able to monetize them and create wealth and institutions.

720
01:42:05,480 --> 01:42:16,480
Now, that given even today's discussion about who gets cut off and who doesn't, you know, I mean, that is a radical concept.

721
01:42:16,480 --> 01:42:21,480
Nothing I said about what we should be doing is radical.

722
01:42:21,480 --> 01:42:25,480
What is radical is who is included in the conversation.

723
01:42:25,480 --> 01:42:44,480
I mean, and to me, you know, that is a lesson that we have to talk to the young people about because they keep looking back at what we did in the 50s, 60s, and so forth and trying to figure out whether the lessons learned.

724
01:42:44,480 --> 01:42:53,480
The lessons learned has to be the broadest inclusion of people, not the particular act or so forth.

725
01:42:53,480 --> 01:42:59,480
What we did, that is what we have to figure out and how do we now put that in an economic context.

726
01:42:59,480 --> 01:43:04,480
Seems to me that is what I'm interested in doing going forward.

727
01:43:04,480 --> 01:43:08,480
Mr. Cox, I really want to thank you. It's been an honor and a privilege to appreciate your time.

728
01:43:08,480 --> 01:43:17,480
Now, you've done your homework. I mean, I must say, I mean, what do you do?

729
01:43:17,480 --> 01:43:22,480
I mean, I just so, so I mean, you definitely cleared it your history.

730
01:43:22,480 --> 01:43:31,480
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

